                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.113/471.</note>
                <head ana="#head_untitled-inferred-from-preceding-sibling-head">[Untitled]</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Mexico</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-04-25T15:00:00-06:36">
                            <hi rend="italic">April 25, 1912—3 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Department’s April 24, 11 a.m. Minister this morning stated his utmost good
                    disposition in the matter, but that he was suffering from a lack of cooperation
                    in matters affecting his Department and from antiquated methods of dispatching
                    public business. I believe that the Minister is sincere in his expressions, but
                    I believe that a spirit of obstruction exists in the War Department and perhaps
                    elsewhere.</p>
                <pb facs="0918" n="802" xml:id="pg_802"/>
                <p>The exact language of the Department’s telegram was read to him but no memorandum
                    was asked for or left, nor shall I treat the matter formally unless otherwise
                    instructed.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Wilson.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
